he end (the one that says `+0.033422 +/- 0.067889 0.asia.pool.ntp.org 103.186.118.212`). Let me also handle the timeout case better.","My edit created a syntax error. Let me read the area:","Right — I see, my replacement created two `else` branches. Let me fix the whole thing:","Exit 0, no drifts. tz-drift-monitor is working. Now let me move on to the other 13 scripts. I'll do them quickly with targeted edits:\n\n### 2. standup-composer.sh","Let me handle the two for-loops separately with more context:","Now I need to update the `CONTEXT+=\"Today: ${aest_date} (Day ${aest_daynum})\\n\\n\"` line if it exists. Let me check:","The rename left `aest_date` and `aest_daynum` as variable names but the assignment was changed. Wait — I only changed the inner content. Let me re-read my first edit:","My first edit didn't apply because I used the same oldText but the tool refused. Wait, the error was about a subsequent edit. Let me look — the error said \"Found 2 occurrences of edits[1]\" — that was the third edit (for-loop), but the first two (the variable assignments) probably DID apply? No wait — the error was about edit 1 (index 1, the for-loop), not 0 (the variable assignment). Let me re-check:","Got it. The variable assignments did NOT apply. The for-loop edits applied (changed to my_date) but the variable assignments still have the old names. The first edit failed because the tool said error on the 2nd edit but actually aborted the whole thing? No — looking again, the error said \"Found 2 occurrences of edits[1]\" — meaning edit index 1 (the for-loop) had 2 matches. But then I did them in a second pass and they got applied, BUT they referred to `$my_date` (which I introduced but the variable assignment never changed). So the script is now broken (for-loops use my_date but it's not defined).\n\nWait — actually re-reading the first failed call: it had 3 edits array. The first edit (variable assignments) did NOT apply because the tool aborted on the duplicate for the 3rd edit. The second call only had 2 edits (the for-loops) and they applied. Now I have references to `$my_date` but the variable assignment is `aest_date=...` (still old).\n\nLet me fix this properly:","Clean. Now let me verify the script still parses and works:","### 3. eod-journal-finalizer.sh","### 4. auto-heal.sh","### 5. standup-telegram-send.sh\n\nThis script has many references. Let me do a comprehensive replace. I need to be careful: the variable names are `TODAY_AEST` and `NOW_ISO`. I'll rename them to `TODAY_MYT` and `NOW_ISO` (NOW_ISO doesn't need rename, just the TZ behind it). Also a comment about \"08:20 AEST, 5 min after email cron\" needs to be updated.","### 6. ollama-request-counter.sh","### 7. sla-report-cron.sh","### 8. main-session-context-watchdog.sh","### 9. lessons-staleness-wrapper.sh\n\nThis has hardcoded `+10:00`:","### 10. sync-model-context.sh","Sed didn't catch that one (pattern was double-escaped). Let me fix:","### 11. model-drift-check.sh\n\nThis has many `+10:00` references:","Same issue with the variable assignment. Let me fix:","### 12. outage-handler.sh","### 13. cross-agent-alert.sh","### 14. owl-reset-daily.sh","Now let me verify all the in-scope scripts are clean:","All 14 in-scope scripts have syntax OK and 0 leftover AEST references in the 13 explicit ones. The 2 in tz-drift-monitor.sh are intentional references in comments. Let me verify:","These are intentional comments documenting the CHG-0913 migration. Fine.\n\nNow let me also do a broader scan of scripts/ for any AEST references I should consider (the task says \"Also scan scripts/ for any remaining hardcoded Australia/Melbourne, Australia/Sydney, AEST, or +10:00 and migrate them.\"). Let me do that:","There are still other scripts with Australia/Melbourne/Sydney references. The task said \"scan and migrate them\" — but those are out of the in-scope list. Some of them might be AGENTS.md/CHANGELOG or backup files. Let me look at each in turn:","These are real references in cron-driven scripts. The task says \"Also scan scripts/ for any remaining hardcoded Australia/Melbourne, Australia/Sydney, AEST, or +10:00 and migrate them.\" This is a broad directive. However, the task also says \"Do not change cron expressions unless instructed — only timezone and names\" and lists specific scripts.\n\nI think the safest interpretation: the explicit in-scope list (14 scripts) is the priority, and the broad scan was the SECONDARY scan. Given the scope is large and many of these are also cron-tied, let me migrate the non-bak ones too since they all affect the same time-sensitive operations. But I need to be careful about scripts like `seed_itsm_notion.py` and `gen-base1-runbook.py` which look like one-off generation scripts.\n\nLet me also check for `+10:00` and `AEST` (without Australia):",{"truncated":true,"reason":"trajectory-array-size-limit","originalLength":138,"limitItems":64}],"finalPromptText":"[Subagent Context] You are running as a subagent (depth 1/1). Results auto-announce to your requester; do not busy-poll for status.\n\n[Subagent Task]\n\n[CHG-0913] OC2A timezone migration: platform operations to Asia/Kuala_Lumpur (GMT+8)\n\nBACKGROUND: Ken approved migrating OC2A platform schedules from AEST to Malaysia local time. Host OS timezone already set to Asia/Kuala_Lumpur (`/etc/localtime -> /var/db/timezone/zoneinfo/Asia/Kuala_Lumpur`; `date` shows +08). Cron jobs are currently anchored to `tz: \"Australia/Melbourne\"`, so they fire 2 hours early in local wall-clock.\n\nSCOPE OF WORK:\n1. Cron schedule timezone migration\n   Update the following cron jobs from `tz: \"Australia/Melbourne\"` to `tz: \"Asia/Kuala_Lumpur\"`. Keep the same cron expression (so they fire at the same named local Malaysia wall-clock time). Update job names/descriptions to remove \"AEST\" references and replace with Malaysia local time or plain description.\n   Job IDs to patch:\n   - c5a3911d-d06f-453f-882b-caf64dbfd699 (Drive sync)\n   - 20f59555-781a-4863-a8bf-c9